		<credit project="CfPBoK@https://slebok.github.io/cfpbok/"/>
		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2012 SI"></a><br><code>sle2012s/paper07</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2012 SI</a> paper:</span><br><i>Specification of temporal properties with OCL</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/BilalKanso.html">Bilal Kanso</a>, <a href="../profile/SafouanTaha.html">Safouan Taha</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.scico.2014.02.029">10.1016/j.scico.2014.02.029</a></li>
<li>Extended version of <a href="../sle2012/paper05.html"><em>Temporal Constraint Support for OCL</em></a> (SLE 2012)</li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagM">T5D: Formal Methods</span></a><ul><li> The main contribution is a formal property-specification framework (temporal extension of OCL) with formal semantics and translation to automata.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1c.html"><span class="tagL">T1C: Behavioural Semantics</span></a><ul><li> The paper adds behavioural/temporal semantics (scenario-based) on top of OCL’s traditionally static constraint focus.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> Tooling is central: the approach is integrated into the Eclipse OCL plug-in and supported by an implementation pipeline.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5c.html"><span class="tagL">T5C: Testing</span></a><ul><li> The framework is connected to automatic test generators via the automata translation, tying the contribution to testing practice.
</li></ul></li></ul>
		<clear/>
		<footer/>
